{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472985"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.8,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"6054"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"},{"type":"tags","id":"6585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11093"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department after falling off a trampoline and injuring his elbow. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. There is an obvious deformity of the elbow and the overlying skin is intact. His hand is cool, pale and the distal pulses are reduced in volume. An X-ray is performed (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/34fd6c57-4b01-4f21-8d04-0b1fc15567b0.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Backslab","Collar and cuff support","Fracture reduction","Fasciotomy","Arm elevation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray indicates a Type III supracondylar humerus fracture, as the anterior humeral line does not intersect the capitellum and there is posterior cortical displacement. Supracondylar fractures are the most common elbow fracture in children age 5-8 years old. Type I fractures have no displacement and do not required reduction. Type II fractures generally require closed reduction +/- fixation and Type III require reduction and internal fixation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires urgent \u003Cstrong\u003Efracture reduction\u003C/strong\u003E due to the vascular compromise evidenced by the cool, pale hand and reduced distal pulses. The displaced fracture is likely impacting on the brachial artery, which may lead to ischaemia and potential compartment syndrome if not addressed promptly. Most Type III fractures will ultimately require surgical reduction with percutaneous pinning under general anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBackslab\u003C/strong\u003E or sling may be used \u003Cstrong\u003Eafter\u003C/strong\u003E the fracture has been reduced or in the event of an undisplaced fracture. \u003Cstrong\u003EArm elevation\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it will not provide support to the fracture and may result in pain from trying to reposition the arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollar and cuff\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of arm sling that is generally used in conjunction with a forearm or upper arm cast to allow for better reduction of the fracture. It may be used in this case following reduction and plaster cast application.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efasciotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure used to relieve compartment syndrome. The signs of compartment syndrome are pain, pallor, paraesthesia, pulselessness and paralysis. Type II fractures very rarely result in vascular injury, however the patient will need to be monitored for signs of impending compartment syndrome. Type III fractures have the highest risk of vascular injury and have an increased risk of developing compartment syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type III supracondylar fractures are completely displaced and have the highest risk of vascular injury.","Urgent fracture reduction is required for supracondylar fractures with vascular compromise to restore blood flow and prevent compartment syndrome.","Following reduction, most Type III supracondylar fractures require percutaneous pinning for stabilisation."],"references":["Supracondylar fracture of the humerus . Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/fractures/Supracondylar_fracture_of_the_humerus_Emergency_Department/","Elbow Fractures in Children. OrthoInfo. June 2019. Available from: https://orthoinfo.aaos.org/en/diseases--conditions/elbow-fractures-in-children/","Supracondylar Fracture - Pediatric. OrthoBullets. June 2025. Available from: https://www.orthobullets.com/pediatrics/4007/supracondylar-fracture--pediatric"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17207"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17207","links"